<HEADLINE>
<P>
PLUTONIUM THREAT OF GALILEO PROBE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Planetary exploration at any risk? 
</P>
<P>
NASA's scheduled shuttle launch on Oct. 12 will bring with it 48 pounds of 
plutonium aboard Project Galileo. As the Challenger disaster tragically 
illustrated in 1986, NASA's space program is not infallible. Furthermore, it is 
believed by some scientists that the plutonium-fueled generator casings are not 
capable of withstanding an accident like Challenger. An even distribution of 
this plutonium is unlikely, but exposure to intense radioactivity now threatens 
many Florida residents if an accident were to occur. 
</P>
<P>
Therefore I ask, should life on Earth be jeopardized by this approach to the 
exploration of Jupiter's atmosphere? Let us insist on the implementation of 
technologies that protect (not threaten) the health of our own planet. 
</P>
<P>
NANCY OWENS-RENNER 
</P>
<P>
San Diego 
</P>
</TEXT>
