<P>
STARS &amp; STRIPES MILITARY PAPERS TO SHED TOP BRASS, DON CIVVIES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times wire services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
WASHINGTON 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The armed services newspaper Stars &amp; Stripes will be run in the future by 
civilians instead of military officers, the Pentagon's spokesman said today. 
</P>
<P>
Both the European and Pacific editions of Stars &amp; Stripes -- originally 
designed to serve as a hometown paper for U.S. forces overseas -- have been 
plagued in recent years by allegations of censorship, and in some cases 
employee harassment. 
</P>
<P>
A Pentagon-appointed ombudsman is in the Pacific looking into the allegations. 
</P>
<P>
"When the current military editors retire, it is our intention to put civilians 
in there," Defense Department spokesman Pete Williams said in an interview. 
</P>
<P>
Williams said the Pentagon is also "looking into" the possible financial and 
editorial consolidation of the newspaper's two editions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
