</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times wire services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
TOKYO 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Isuzu Motors Co., Japan's commercial vehicle maker, announced today it will 
sell heavy-duty tractors imported from Volvo Truck Corp. of Sweden, starting in 
March next year. 
</P>
<P>
The Tokyo-based company said a formal agreement on import and sales of Volvo's 
F16 tractors in Japan has been concluded between the two companies. 
</P>
<P>
"The agreement is part of our company's globalization program and is aimed at 
meeting the needs of the diversifying domestic market," Isuzu President Kazuo 
Tobiyama said at a news conference. 
</P>
<P>
"Isuzu believes this Volvo tractor will meet the expanding requirements of the 
Japanese heavy-duty transport market," he added. 
</P>
<P>
"We hope our heavy-duty tractors will have a strong appeal to the Japanese 
market," said Sten Langenius, president of Volvo Truck Corp. "The Swedish 
tractor industry has achieved fully international operations over the last 10 
years." 
</P>
